Bid Alert No.:  12022838
Agency Bid No.:  36C24520Q0153
Title:  NOTICE OF INTENT TO SOLE SOURCE VCL TEXTING PLATFORM TO: CROSS LINK MEDIA, LLC (SB); CAGE: 6E5J4 EDA: 1/31/2020
Received Date:  01/14/2020
Close Date:  Not Stated
Delivery Point:  1701 DIRECTORS BLVD LINTHICUM MD 21090
Download documents online
Bid Documents
Request Future Documents
Specifications:
STATEMENT OF WORK Cross Link Media, LLC Texting Dashboard and Services Part 1: Scope of Work To provide a texting platform that will allow Veterans and family members, in crisis, to communicate with the Veterans Crisis Line (VCL), via short message service (SMS) messaging, by way of a vanity short code VETALK (838255). The platform would need to be configured to accommodate the vanity short code leased by the VCL. 1.1 Description of Services: The service will need to be able to provide a dashboard type interface that will allow employees to carry on multiple texting sessions. The service will trigger an automated response immediately, based on key words in the original message received from the texter. The VCL employee would then respond back to the texter via the dashboard interface which would be accessible on their desktop. The service would allow access to the VCL employee through the internet and will not store or retain any of the information from the text session on any server or archive. The texting dashboard would need to allow access to the texters phone number, which would be especially useful in crisis situations. 1.2 Background: There are approximately 25 million Veterans in the United States and 5 million Veterans who receive care within VHA. Data from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention indicate suicide rates among men between the ages of 20 and 65 at approximately 22 per 100,000 persons per year. VHA mental health officials estimate 6,400 suicides per year among Veterans, and 1,600 - 1,800 among Veterans receiving health care from VHA. Recent reports have suggested that Veterans may be at an increased risk for conditions and behaviors associated with poor mental health including post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), anxiety, depression, and increased rates of substance use; all of which are established risk factors for suicide. For many Veterans in emotional crisis, their first contact with VHA is though the VCL. In an effort to reduce the number of suicides among the Veteran population, a texting program is being established to provide another access point-of-care for the Veteran population. Text messaging is a useful tool for reaching specific audiences. Historically, the VCL only had staff utilizing the texting platform at the Canandaigua site. In 2019, the VCL expanded this service to be conducted at the Atlanta site as well, to meet with increasing new media (SMS) demand. 1.3 Objective: The key component required will be a web-accessed interface allowing a remote operator to receive and send responses to an individual mobile phone commonly referred to as a Dashboard, which will be integrated with the SMSC Gateway provided by a third party. 1.4 Period of Performance: The period of performance shall be for one (1) base six (6) month period as follows: Base period: 31 January 2020 through 31 July 2020 1.5 Termination of Services: The VCL reserves the right to terminate any or all services if they are determined to be no longer necessary. 1.6 Transition Plan: Contractor shall provide a transition plan to ensure that there is no lapse in critical services. Part 2: TASKS AND DELIVERABLES 2.1 Description of Tasks: Deliver dashboard functionality through a web-based URL, to allow VCL employees the capability to receive and respond to text messages from any mobile telephone and other service. No data will be stored, saved or otherwise archived from texting other than statistics necessary for billing and accounting purposes. The contractor will need to coordinate with the VCL to establish a suite of automated, instantaneous responses to initial text, based on keywords in the original text message received. The contractor must also provide texting capability, both sending and receiving, for the predetermined vanity short code (which is being provided through a separate procurement). The services should include all fees, etc. for a flat rate. 2.2 Deliverables: 1. Dashboard Functional Requirements: Once an MO (mobile originated message) is received at the SMSC, two actions will happen: First, an automatic response will be generated to the sender based on the key word received. Key words can be changed at any time as can responses. Automatic response can be several phrases/input patterns deep. Requires ability to set time for generating response for each layer. An alert will be sent to the VCL stating that a message has been received and response has been sent initiating the interaction via the Dashboard. Automatic response disengagement. A button will appear allowing an operator to disengage the automatic response mechanism and take control of the outbound text messages. Dashboard will display telephone number of originating mobile device, display location based on area code and geographic location of the phone at that moment. Dashboard will display original inbound key word sent to short code. Time and date stamp will reflect receipt of inbound message. Dashboard will display outbound response based on inbound key word. Dashboard will display further inbound and outbound messages. Inbound messages will be highlighted by a different color than outbound messages. Dialog summary retain entire conversation until terminated and display in a scrolling log. Operator will be able to terminate dialog based on criteria established by VCL staff. Terminate button will appear on screen and be highlighted in Red. A double opt in to terminate will be required. Operator will be able to Save Dialog for output to Word or other format as determined by VCL staff Dependent on current instant messaging guidelines developed by the VCL. A notes section will appear for an operator to make notes on the record while engaged in the message originator. Note section will have unlimited space and will scroll forward as information is input. Message, summaries, phone numbers and personal information will not be housed outside any VA facility. A shared inbox or lobby for purposes of supervision and claiming due to technical difficulties. 2. Documentation and Training a. Will need to provide appropriate system documentation and training.
View numbered notes for details if one is referred to in the specifications

Specifications:
Notice of Intent to Award Noncompetitive Procurement Metro-Area Networking and Voice-over IP (VoIP) solution for the state of Hawaii. The U.S. Geological Survey, Volcano Sciences Center (VSC) and the Hawaiian Volcano Observatory (HVO), has a requirement for an integrated Metro-Area Networking and Voice-over IP (VoIP) solution for the state of Hawaii. HVO's requirement for MAN infrastructure consists of the following technical requirements at each of the listed locations: HVO Ironworks Ethernet service: Bandwidth 100 Mbps VoIP phone service: 30 phone numbers with handsets. HVO Milo St Warehouse Ethernet service: Bandwidth 10 Mbps, VoIP phone service, and 8 phone numbers with handsets. Kawaihae Datacenter (KDC) Ethernet service: Bandwidth 100 Mbps, Datacenter co-location 48U cabinet space. HVO old observatory building Ethernet service: Bandwidth 10 Mbps Volcano National Park AT&T Cell Site (HAVO): Ethernet service: Bandwidth 10 Mbps The period of performance for this service will be one year (01 March 2020 - 28 February 2021) and two option years (01 March 2021 - 28 February 2022 and 01 March 2022 - 28 February 2023). The Government intends to negotiate on a non-competitive basis with Hawaiian Telcom, Inc. of Honolulu Hawaii, in accordance with Federal Acquisition Regulation (FAR) 13.106-1(b), only one source reasonably available and FAR 13.501. Hawaiian Telcom, Inc. is the only interisland local exchange carrier (LEC) of voice and network services. They are the only carrier to have the infrastructure (including copper and fiber optic cabling) to USGS locations at the Hilo NWS Office on the Big Island. Hawaiian Telcom, Inc. is the only carrier to provide multiprotocol label switching (MPLS) services over a fault tolerant interisland network. They are the only carrier to provide Ethernet based virtual local area network (vLAN) services over an MPLS network. The anticipated purchase order will be firm fixed price. The NAICS code for this action is 517311; Wired Telecommunications Carriers for which the associated size standard is 1,500 employees. This is not a request for quotation, and the Government does not intend to pay for information received. A determination by the Government not to compete this requirement, based upon responses to this notice, is solely within the discretion of the Government. Respondents will not be notified of the results of any Government evaluation of the information received. All questions and submissions in response to this notice must be submitted electronically via email to the Contracting Officer at sklingler@usgs.gov before the closing date (01/29/2020) of this announcement. All responsible sources may submit a capability statement, proposal or quotation, which shall be considered by the agency, to the Contracting Officer no later than the closing date of this announcement.

Title:  Market Research - RFI- Enterprise TPBO Pager Service Modernization
Received Date:  01/14/2020
Close Date:  01/23/2020  Est.
Delivery Point:  23 CHRISTOPHER WAY EATONTOWN NJ 07724
Download documents online
Bid Documents
Request Future Documents
Specifications:
Pager Modernization Project TAC Number: TAC-20-57099 Page 14 of 33 This is a request for information (RFI) only. Do not submit a proposal or quote. As a part of the Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) Technology Acquisition Center (TAC) market research process, this request for information (RFI) will be used to determine the availability of a Commercial-Off-The-Shelf (COTS) WiFi -based paging software application (mobile app) solution that can be included in VA s app catalog and used on VA smartphones. VA requires a COTS WIFI-based paging system solution that allows users to transmit and receive pages using VA smartphones enterprise wide. There is no obligation on the part of the Government to acquire any products or services described in this RFI. Your response to this RFI will be treated only as information for the Government to consider. You will not be entitled to payment for direct or indirect costs that you incur in responding to this RFI. This request does not constitute a solicitation for proposals or the authority to enter into negotiations to award a contract. Interested parties are responsible for adequately marking proprietary, restricted or competition sensitive information contained in their response. The Government does not intend to pay for the information submitted in response to this RFI. Responses to this RFI are requested by 12:00 P.M. Eastern Time on January 22, 2020. Please provide the following in your responses: 1. A capabilities statement that addresses the questions below. If additional information is required by VA to determine a contractor s capability to provide the full requirement and the economic feasibility of the information provided, additional information may be requested later. A draft version of the requirement is below. Please direct all responses to Joe Jones, joseph.jones6@va.gov and Debra Clayton, debra.clayton2@va.gov . 2. Pricing models to obtain your product/services that would be most advantageous to the Government; 3. Breakout of software, hardware and services necessary for the installation and maintenance of the mobile app solution; 4. Describe the options for hosting your system 5. Any Contract Vehicle of which you are a part that can be used to acquire your solution as well as the company business size and status for each vehicle as designated by the NAICS 517312 and the U.S. Small Business Administration (i.e., Large Business, Small Business, Service-Disabled Veteran Owned Small Business, Small Disadvantaged Business, Women-Owned Small Business, Hub Zone Small Business, etc.) PRODUCT REQUIREMENTS VA requires a Commercial-Off-The-Shelf (COTS) WiFi based paging system solution for VA to add to the VA app catalog and use on VA iPhones. The Contractor shall provide a COTS WIFI based paging system solution that allows users to transmit and receive pages using their smartphones enterprise wide. The solution shall meet the following requirements: Includes a perpetual enterprise license for an unlimited number of users. Has a valid federal Authorization-To-Operate (ATO) to reference for the security quote. Operates on iOS. Must be a life safety system IAW VA s Telecommunications Design Manual. Shall be Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPPA)-compliant, Personal Health Information (PHI) compliant, and Federal Information Processing Standards (FIPS)-compliant. Is wireless carrier agnostic/carrier neutral application (i.e. has to work on all smartphones). Has secure messaging capability application that allows users to utilize a pager number, send electronic page utilizing an app that s carrier neutral (can be LTE/WiFi). Shows a trail of when page was sent, read, and received, i.e. a page tracking log. Deliverable: Installation and User Guide GRAY MARKET GOODS The Contractor must provide only new equipment and new parts for the required products described herein; no used, refurbished, or remanufactured equipment or parts shall be provided under any circumstances. Absolutely no Gray Market Goods or Counterfeit Electronic Parts shall be provided. Gray Market Goods are defined as genuine branded goods intentionally or unintentionally sold outside of an authorized sales-territory or by non-authorized dealers in an authorized territory. All equipment shall be accompanied by the Original Equipment Manufacturers (OEM s) warranty. Counterfeit Electronic Parts are defined as unlawful or unauthorized reproduction, substitution, or alteration that has been knowingly mismarked, misidentified, or otherwise misrepresented to be an authentic, unmodified electronic part from the original manufacturer, or a source with the express written authority of the original manufacturer or current design activity, including an authorized aftermarket manufacturer. Unlawful or unauthorized substitution includes used electronic parts represented as new, or the false identification of grade, serial number, lot number, date code, or performance characteristics. NOTICE OF THE FEDERAL ACCESSIBILITY LAW AFFECTING ALL INFORMATION AND COMMUNICATION TECHNOLOGY (ICT) PROCUREMENTS (SECTION 508) On January 18, 2017, the Architectural and Transportation Barriers Compliance Board (Access Board) revised and updated, in a single rulemaking, standards for electronic and information technology developed, procured, maintained, or used by Federal agencies covered by Section 508 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973, as well as our guidelines for telecommunications equipment and customer premises equipment covered by Section 255 of the Communications Act of 1934. The revisions and updates to the Section 508-based standards and Section 255-based guidelines are intended to ensure that information and communication technology (ICT) covered by the respective statutes is accessible to and usable by individuals with disabilities. SECTION 508 INFORMATION AND COMMUNICATION TECHNOLOGY (ICT) STANDARDS The Section 508 standards established by the Access Board are incorporated into, and made part of all VA orders, solicitations and purchase orders developed to procure ICT. These standards are found in their entirety at: https://www.access-board.gov/guidelines-and-standards/communications-and-it/about-the-ict-refresh/final-rule/text-of-the-standards-and-guidelines. A printed copy of the standards will be supplied upon request.  Federal agencies must comply with the updated Section 508 Standards beginning on January 18, 2018. The Final Rule as published in the Federal Register is available from the Access Board: https://www.access-board.gov/guidelines-and-standards/communications-and-it/about-the-ict-refresh/final-rule. The Contractor shall comply with 508 Chapter 2: Scoping Requirements for all electronic ICT and content delivered under this contract. Specifically, as appropriate for the technology and its functionality, the Contractor shall comply with the technical standards marked here: E205 Electronic Content (Accessibility Standard -WCAG 2.0 Level A and AA Guidelines) E204 Functional Performance Criteria E206 Hardware Requirements E207 Software Requirements E208 Support Documentation and Services Requirements COMPATIBILITY WITH ASSISTIVE TECHNOLOGY The standards do not require installation of specific accessibility-related software or attachment of an assistive technology device. Section 508 requires that ICT be compatible with such software and devices so that ICT can be accessible to and usable by individuals using assistive technology, including but not limited to screen readers, screen magnifiers, and speech recognition software. ACCEPTANCE AND ACCEPTANCE TESTING Deliverables resulting from this solicitation will be accepted based in part on satisfaction of the Section 508 Chapter 2: Scoping Requirements standards identified above. The Government reserves the right to test for Section 508 Compliance before delivery. The Contractor shall be able to demonstrate Section 508 Compliance upon Deliverables resulting from this solicitation will be accepted based in part on satisfaction of the Section 508 Chapter 2: Scoping Requirements standards identified above. GENERAL REQUIREMENTS VA TECHNICAL REFERENCE MODEL The Contractor shall support the VA enterprise management framework. In association with the framework, the Contractor shall comply with OI&T Technical Reference Model (VA TRM). The VA TRM is one component within the overall Enterprise Architecture (EA) that establishes a common vocabulary and structure for describing the information technology used to develop, operate, and maintain enterprise applications. Moreover, the VA TRM, which includes the Standards Profile and Product List, serves as a technology roadmap and tool for supporting OI&T. Architecture & Engineering Services (AES) has overall responsibility for the VA TRM.

Title:  Short-Term Rental Compliance Services
Received Date:  01/14/2020
Close Date:  02/07/2020  11:00 AM

Specifications:
Specifications include, but are not limited to: ssist with administration of a short-term rental program, including address identification and data reporting, compliance monitoring, enforcement, and tax collection support.In recent years, many cities have created rules and regulations in response to the growth of the short-term rental (STR) industry facilitated by online platforms such as AirBnB, HomeAway, VRBO, and Flipkey. In 2017, the City began to examine the state of the STR industry within the city in response to concerns voiced by citizen groups over safety, nuisance activity, and potential loss of neighborhood character due to the increase in STR activity, as well as concerns over the potential loss of Transient Occupancy Tax (TOT) not being collected from the residential short-term rentals.Following a series of studies and public participation events, in December 2018, the City Council directed the City Attorney to prepare an ordinance to implement the regulation of STRs with specified limitations. A short-term rental ordinance is currently under review and will likely be adopted in the coming months. Key elements of the proposed ordinance include the following:1. A STR host would be required to register with the City and obtain a unique STR registration identification number valid for one year.2. A STR host may operate up to two non-primary residence STRs or three if one STR is a primary residence.3. Non-primary residence STRs in multi-family buildings will be limited based on a sliding scale.4. The number of guests will be limited to two guests per bedroom plus two, for a maximum of ten guests per STR with outdoor quiet hours in effect between 10:00 p.m. and 7:00 a.m.5. A local 24-hour contact person will have to be available to respond to complaints within one hour.6. An Occasional Event Permit will be required to host special events in STRs.7. An optional ban on un-hosted STRs may be implemented by a vote of property owners within a geographic area. (It is anticipated that City staff will administer this option).8. Hosting platforms shall not process or complete any booking transaction for any STR unless a valid STR registration number has been issued by the City.9. Enforcement measures including the issuance of fines for noncompliance.10. Remittance of the Citys 12 percent TOT.The ideal Consultant should provide solutions for addressing the regulations as discussed aboveand describe how the cost would be structured for these services.

Title:  EOHHS Market-Based ENS Initiative
Received Date:  12/03/2019
Close Date:  01/17/2020  04:00 PM
Purchase Type:  Term:
Delivery Point:  Massachusetts
Delivery Date:  Not Stated

Amendment 1 (01/14/2020)
Amendment 2 (01/14/2020)
Amendment 3 (01/14/2020)
Specifications:
The Statewide ENS Framework will consist of ENS Vendor Applicants certified by EOHHS who will be responsible for collecting ADTs, sharing ADTs, and providing notification to providers. Under 101 CMR 20.00, all acute care hospitals will be required to submit ADT data to at least one of these Certified ENS Vendors. Certified ENS Vendors will be required to share the ADTs it collects pursuant to the submission requirements with all other Certified ENS Vendors. Thus, the Statewide ENS Framework will make a universal data set of ADTs available to ENS Recipients, allowing them to subscribe to a single Certified ENS Vendor and receive notifications from any acute care hospital in the state. The Certified ENS Vendors will be expected to run matching algorithms on the ADT data it receives to generate notification to ENS Recipients. If there is no match against its clients patient panels, the Certified ENS Vendor must delete the ADT.
 
Product Code(s): 91500, 20447, 92000, 92064

Specifications:
Specifications include, but are not limited to: CVC administers victim claims by utilizing a web-based claim and billing management system IBM Case Management system that is referred to as the Crime Victims Management System (CVMS). Medical and other providers of services to victims/claimants submit billing documents to CVC which are imaged and stored in CVMS. In addition, victims of crime may submit their application and medical bills online via the CVC Web Portal.Computer and systems support for CVC is currently provided by the Information Technology Support Division of the OAG. The automated system provides data interchange by SSH file transfer protocol (or secure file transfer protocol) (SFTP) between the current medical cost containment vendor and the OAG system(s). There are multiple separate electronic data interchanges (EDIs) utilizing secure SFTP between OAG/CVC and the current cost containment vendor as follows:Billing Data: OAG/CVC receives from cost containment vendor, on a daily basis, completed billing data on cost-contained bills;Explanation of Benefits - OAG/CVC receives from the cost containment vendor, on a daily basis, an electronic copy of all the Explanation of Benefits (EOB) for each days transmissions.The CVC Act requires the CVC program to pay health care services according to the medical fee guidelines as prescribed in Subtitle A, Title 5, Labor Code (Workers Comp Act). These medical fee guidelines (MFG), as promulgated by the Texas Department of Insurances Division of Workers Compensation (DWC) in Chapter 134 of the Texas Administrative Code, explain the method of cost containment (CC) for medical services, such as physician fees, inpatient hospital expenses, and ambulatory surgical center expenses, to be utilized by the CVC program and its CC services vendor. CVC will accept bills from medical providers up to three years after the date services were rendered, unless good cause exists to accept the bills after that time. The date of service determines which MFG schedule is used to cost contain the bill. When no MFG exists, bills should be paid at a fair and reasonable amount as determined solely by the OAG. CVC does not participate in any PPO discount programs.

Title:  Design Thinking for building NGSS capacity
Received Date:  12/23/2019
Close Date:  01/02/2020  01:00 PM
Purchase Type:  Not Stated
Delivery Point:  Oregon Institute of Technology, Klamath Falls, Oregon
Delivery Date:  Not Stated
Download documents online
Bid Documents
Awards
Specifications:
Specifications include, but are not limited to: The overall project seeks to develop the capacity for use of Design Thinking strategies amongeducational leaders in the Portland Metro and South Metro-Salem STEM Partnerships.Specifically, two cohorts of principals and teachers will use Design Thinking as a process to drive ashift in their schools culture of teaching and learning. Design Thinking will be presented as bothan instructional strategy as well as a strategy for making change. This process of capacity building will ultimately serve to help schools meaningfully adopt the new NGSS framework for teachingand learning science.Each of two regional cohorts (SMPS and PMSP) will comprise 10 school-based teams, eachincluding one administrator/principal and two teacher-leaders (20 teams total: 20 principals, 40teachers). The lead contractor will develop and deliver a series of regional workshops and sitebased, small-group coaching experiences that support both the learning of the design thinkingprocess as well as the development of at least two design-based instructional units (teachers) andmini-projects aimed to practice design thinking as a strategy for change (principals). Thecontractor will coordinate expertise as needed to engage site-based teams in collaborative designthinking focused on specific, locally-relevant challenges related to implementation of NGSS.NGSS expertise may be identified and contracted independently by SMSP/Oregon Tech to supportthe Quoter, or the Quoter may choose to include internal expertise as a portion of their projectbudget.
